Article published on widely read website</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>544fc693af1922.62219078</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>18000</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Industry Funding</gtr:description><gtr:end>2014-07-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Federation of Small Business (FSB)</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>N/A</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>35AA6642-1AE0-4B96-B684-F3D4053E2F4A</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>546456e9d15454.05172039</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2014-03-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>The findings have been used to provide research-based evidence to inform the debate over Scottish independence by governments, industry, the media and the public. Examples include: 

(1) Trade bodies, particularly Financials Services Enterprise (FSE), which represents financial institutions in Scotland, the Institute of Directors (IoD) and ICAS have directed their members to the papers written as part of the ESRC Senior Fellowship to help inform their voting decisions.
(2) The findings from the ESRC project have received widespread media attention both in the UK and worldwide (please see 'Engagement Activities' for further details).
(3) Briefings have been given to the EU, UK and Scottish Governments, including a briefing directly with Danny Alexander MP, Chief Secretary to the Treasury. The work was cited by the UK Treasury Scotland Analysis in their paper on defence.
(4) The findings were included in 'Scotland's Decisions: 16 Questions to think about for the referendum on September 18th', published in conjunction with the David Hume Institute, which had over 100,000 downloads.
(5) Public lectures were given in Aberdeen, Brussels, Edinburgh, Glasgow, London and St Andrews. 
(6) Five briefings with diplomats from Canada, Denmark, Japan, Sweden, and the USA were given at their request. 
(7) It's led to giving evidence to both the BIS Parliamentary Select Committee inquiry into business attitudes towards the UK-EU referendum (2016), and the the Scottish Economy, Jobs and Fair Work Committee (2016).</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2014</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>C50EF120-9A42-41F3-B2CD-7DE2C560BCBB</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>545fcf068b3395.19333450</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Electronics,Energy,Financial Services, and Management Consultancy,Government, Democracy and Justice,Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology,Security and Diplomacy</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The research funded from this grant consisted of 75 semi-structured interviews into the future of the UK and Scotland with senior business leaders in medium and large companies in six industries of strategic importance to Scotland. They include electronics and technology, energy, engineering and industrial manufacturing, financial services, food and drink, and life sciences. 
Evidence from independent, politically-neutral studies of business leader's attitudes towards Scottish independence is relatively consistent. Uncertainty over the currency (with a strong preference for Sterling), EU membership (with a strong preference for remaining in the EU), regulation (with a strong preference for having a common regulatory framework with the rUK), taxation (with a preference for competitive taxation, consistency with the rUK and stability) and the general trading environment, poses a significant challenge to business. The perceived risks associated with such uncertainties expressed by business leaders are highly specific and directly concern business activity. An average of half of business leaders' surveyed cannot identify any opportunities that independence would present for their businesses. Of those able to identify opportunities, they are less specific or unspecific and tend to relate more to the economics and politics of the debate. Only a small minority can identify an opportunity for business investment and growth. 
A majority of business leaders indicate that the potential costs and risks of independence to business outweigh the perceived benefits and opportunities that might occur. Unsurprisingly, PLC companies headquartered in Scotland appear to be more affected than companies headquartered outside of Scotland. Companies supplying to the MoD also report that independence could pose a challenge to their business. A significant number of medium and large companies have the majority of their trade in the rUK (typically 90% rUK, and 10% in Scotland), and appear far more affected than companies whose trade is mainly in Scotland, or is diversified globally. Medium sized, privately owned companies appear more willing to absorb downside risk than PLCs, the latter of who are also concerned about shareholder value. Medium sized, foreign-owned companies trading predominantly in a global market indicate they are less affected by the constitutional debate than PLCs trading primarily in the rUK. Business leaders of smaller medium-sized, private companies exporting globally, and smaller firms whose trade (both customers and suppliers) is predominantly in Scotland are the most likely to emphasise the opportunities presented by the possibility of Scottish independence. 
The findings allowed for a decision-making typology to be developed. Business attitudes towards Scottish independence and decision-making under different constitutional scenarios are clearly influenced by a combination of where the business is domiciled, customer location, headquarter jurisdiction and ownership structure. This report also reviews two other surveys of business attitudes towards Scottish independence. In all three studies reviewed here, approximately 10% of business leaders indicate they may move business activity out of Scotland in the event of a yes outcome.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The findings have already resulted in two book chapters and a published paper. They were disseminated extensively in the lead-up to the refernedum to policy makers, industry bodies and the public. Further theoretical development underpinning the findings, and wider lessons learned about business attitudes/decision-making and political movements will be undertaken with an aim of publishing in highly-regarded academic journals. As the academic theorising work develops, it will be further disseminated to policy-makers through links developed through the project in the Scottish and UK Governments. Public engagement continues with talks at industry events (such as a Chartered Management Institute Conference key-note on November 14th). Commentating in the media will continue.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>751EE356-910C-4D08-9638-EF48C7D07645</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>542d3f9a997bb6.61520765</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Electronics,Energy,Financial Services, and Management Consultancy,Government, Democracy and Justice,Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology,Security and Diplomacy</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.futureukandscotland.ac.uk/sites/default/files/papers/Evidence%20from%20Business%20Summary%20Report%20Final.pdf</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><g